---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base title="Cohort">
  <h1>Cohort</h1>
  <p class="label">Our first research prototype</p>

  <div class="prose">
    <h2>Why We Built Cohort</h2>
    <p>
      As we reviewed research, surveyed students, and conducted interviews, one
      idea kept appearing.
    </p>
    <p>
      Students often said it was easier to stay focused when they knew other
      people were studying too. Academic research pointed in a similar
      direction, suggesting that social presence and accountability can
      influence attention and motivation.
    </p>
    <p>That led us to a simple question:</p>
    <p class="question">
      Can simply knowing your friends are studying alongside you make it easier
      to stay focused?
    </p>
    <p>Cohort is our first attempt to explore that question.</p>

    <h2>Keeping It Simple</h2>
    <p>
      Most study apps include points, streaks, leaderboards, achievements, or
      other forms of gamification.
    </p>
    <p>We intentionally left those out.</p>
    <p>
      A student creates or joins a study session with three to six friends.
      During the session, everyone can see who is present and who has marked
      themselves as focusing.
    </p>
    <p>That's it.</p>
    <p>
      There are no scores to chase, no rankings to climb, and no rewards to
      earn.
    </p>
    <p>
      The goal isn't to build the most feature-rich study app. The goal is to
      isolate one idea and understand whether shared social presence alone can
      make a meaningful difference.
    </p>

    <h2>Why It Matters</h2>
    <p>
      If we added points, badges, or competition, we wouldn't know what was
      actually improving focus.
    </p>
    <p>Was it because students knew their friends were studying?</p>
    <p>Or because they wanted to win?</p>
    <p>
      By keeping Cohort intentionally simple, we can test one variable at a time
      and let the results guide what comes next.
    </p>

    <h2>Current Status</h2>
    <p>Cohort is currently in development.</p>
    <p>
      This fall, we'll invite volunteer high school students to use Cohort
      during the exam period. Alongside testing the prototype, we'll collect
      feedback, observe how students actually use it, and compare the results
      with what we learned during our research phase.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whether our hypothesis is supported or challenged, we'll publish what we
      learn on this website.
    </p>

    <p class="links">
      <span class="muted">GitHub: Coming soon</span>
      <span class="muted">Live Prototype: Coming soon</span>
    </p>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .prose h2 {
    margin-top: 3rem;
  }

  .question {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .links {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 1.5rem;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    margin-top: 2.5rem;
  }
</style>
